example.p:
  \diff{}{x} \{ 4x + 7 \}
  &= 4 \cdot \diff{}{x} \{ x \}  + 7 \cdot \diff{}{x} \{ 1 \} & \text{LIN}

  &= 4 \cdot 1 + 7 \cdot 0 = 4


where we have used LIN with f(x)=x, g(x)=1, \alpha=4, \beta=7.

In the same vein as the previous example, we can use the quotient rule to compute


  \diff{}{x} \left\{ \frac{x}{4x + 7} \right \}
  &= \frac{ (4x+7) \cdot \diff{}{x} \{x\}  - x \cdot \diff{}{x} \{ 4x + 7 \} }{(4x+7)^2}
& \text{QR}

  &= \frac{ (4x+7) \cdot 1  - x \cdot 4 }{(4x+7)^2}

&= \frac{7}{(4x+7)^2}


where we have used the quotient rule QR with f(x) =x and g(x)=4x+7.

This problem looks nasty. But it isn't so hard if we just  build it up a bit at a time.



	First, f(x) is the ratio of


	f_1(x)=x\qquad\text{and}\qquad f_2(x)=2x+\frac{1}{3x+1}


	If we can find the derivatives of f_1(x) and f_2(x), we will be able to get the derivative of f(x) just by applying the quotient rule. The derivative,  f'_1(x)=1, of f_1(x) is easy, so let's work on  f_2(x).



	The function f_2(x) is the linear combination


	f_2(x)=2f_3(x)+f_4(x)\qquad\text{with}\qquad
	f_3(x)=x \quad\text{and}\quad f_4(x)= \frac{1}{3x+1}


	If we can find the derivatives of f_3(x) and f_4(x), we will be able to get the derivative of f_2(x) just by applying linearity  (Theorem). The derivative, f'_3(x)=1, of f_3(x) is easy.  So let's work of f_4(x).



	The function f_4(x) is the ratio

	f_4(x)=\frac{1}{f_5(x)}\qquad\text{with}\qquad f_5(x)=3x+1

	If we can find the derivative of f_5(x), we will be able to get  the derivative of f_4(x) just by applying the special case the quotient rule (Corollary). The derivative of  f_5(x) is easy.



	So we have completed breaking down f(x) into easy pieces. It is now just a matter of reversing the break down steps, putting everything back together, starting with the easy pieces  and working up to f(x). Here goes.


	f_5(x)\amp=3x+1 

        \amp\amp\hskip-1.3in
         \text{ so } \diff{}{x} f_5(x) \amp= 3\diff{}{x} x +\diff{}{x} 1
		=3\cdot 1+0 = 3 & \text{LIN}

	 f_4(x)\amp=\frac{1}{f_5(x)}

        \amp\amp\hskip-1.3in
	\text{ so } \diff{}{x} f_4(x)\amp=-\frac{f'_5(x)}{f_5(x)^2}=-\frac{3}{(3x+1)^2}
						& \text{QR}

	 f_2(x)\amp=2f_3(x)+f_4(x) 

        \amp\amp\hskip-1.3in
            \text{ so }\diff{}{x} f_2(x) \amp= 2f'_3(x)+ f'_4(x)=2-\frac{3}{(3x+1)^2}
						& \text{LIN}

	 f(x)\amp=\frac{f_1(x)}{f_2(x)}

        \amp\amp\hskip-1.3in
           \text{ so }\diff{}{x} f(x)\amp=\frac{f'_1(x)f_2(x)-f_1(x)f'_2(x)}{f_2(x)^2}
						& \text{QR}

        \amp\amp\amp =\frac{1\big[2x+\frac{1}{3x+1}\big]-x\big[2-\frac{3}{(3x+1)^2}\big]}
						   {\big[2x+\frac{1}{3x+1}\big]^2}


	Oof!



	We now have an answer. But we really should clean it up, not only to make it easier to read, but also because invariably such computations are  just small steps inside much larger computations. Any future computations involving this expression will be a lot easier and less error prone  if we clean it up now. Cancelling the 2x and the -2x in


	  1\big[2x+\frac{1}{3x\!+\!1}\big]
					-x\big[2-\frac{3}{(3x\!+\!1)^2}\big]
	&=2x+\frac{1}{3x\!+\!1} -2x+\frac{3x}{(3x\!+\!1)^2}

	&=\frac{1}{3x\!+\!1}+\frac{3x}{(3x\!+\!1)^2}


	and multiplying both the numerator  and denominator by (3x+1)^2 gives


	f'(x)&=\frac{\frac{1}{3x+1}+\frac{3x}{(3x+1)^2}}
						   {\big[2x+\frac{1}{3x+1}\big]^2}
	\ \frac{(3x+1)^2}{(3x+1)^2}

	&=\frac{(3x+1)+3x}{\big[2x(3x+1)+1\big]^2}

	&=\frac{6x+1}{[6x^2+2x+1]^2}.

We'll start by generalising linearity to three functions.


\diff{}{x}\big\{a F(x)+ b G(x)+ c H(x)\big\}
 &=\diff{}{x}\big\{\ a \cdot [F(x)]\ +\ 1\cdot[b G(x)+c H(x)]\ \big\}

   &=a F'(x)+\diff{}{x}\{b G(x)+c H(x)\}

   &\qquad\text{by LIN with $\alpha=a, f(x)=F(x), \beta=1$,}

   &\qquad\text{and } g(x)=b G(x)+c H(x)

   &=a F'(x)+b G'(x)+c H'(x)

   &\qquad\text{by LIN with } \alpha=b, f(x)=G(x), \beta=c,

   &\qquad\text{and } g(x)=H(x)


This gives us linearity for three terms, namely (just replacing upper case names by lower case names)


\diff{}{x}\{af(x)+bg(x)+ch(x)\} =af'(x)+bg'(x)+ch'(x)


Just by repeating the above argument many times, we may generalise to linearity for n terms, for any natural number n:


\amp\diff{}{x}\{a_1f_1(x)+a_2f_2(x)+\cdots+a_n f_n(x)\}

\amp\hskip0.5in=a_1f'_1(x)+a_2f'_2(x)+\cdots+a_n f'_n(x)

In this example we'll compute \diff{}{x}\big\{(3x+9)(x^2+4x^3)\big\} in two different ways. For the first, we'll start with the product rule.


\amp\diff{}{x}\big\{(3x+9)(x^2+4x^3)\big\}

\amp\hskip0.5in=\Big\{\diff{}{x}(3x+9)\Big\}\ (x^2+4x^3)
   +(3x+9)\ \diff{}{x}\{x^2+4x^3\}

\amp\hskip0.5in=\big\{3\times 1+9\times 0\big\}\ (x^2+4x^3)
   +(3x+9)\ \{2x+4(3x^2)\}

\amp\hskip0.5in=3(x^2+4x^3)+(3x+9)\ (2x+12x^2)

\amp\hskip0.5in=3x^2+12x^3+(6x^2+18x+36x^3+108x^2)

\amp\hskip0.5in=18x+117x^2+48x^3


For the second, we expand the product first and then differentiate.


\diff{}{x}\big\{(3x+9)(x^2+4x^3)\big\}
&=\diff{}{x}\big\{9x^2+39x^3+12x^4\big\}

&=9(2x)+39(3x^2)+12(4x^3)

&=18x+117x^2+48x^3

In this example, we'll use the same trickery as in Example  to find the derivative x^{p/q} for any two natural numbers p and q. By definition of the q^{\rm th} root,


x^p= \big(x^{p/q}\big)^q.


That is, x^p and  \big(x^{p/q}\big)^q are the same function, and so have the same  derivative. So we differentiate both of them. We already know that, by Lemma   with n=p,


\diff{}{x}\big\{x^p\big\}=p x^{p-1}


and that, by Lemma with n=q and f(x)=x^{p/q},


\diff{}{x}\big\{\big(x^{p/q}\big)^q\big\}
& = q\ \big(x^{p/q}\big)^{q-1}\ \diff{}{x}\big\{x^{p/q}\big\}


Remember that (x^a)^b = x^{(a \cdot b)}. Now these two derivatives  must be the same. So


p x^{p-1} &=q\cdot x^{(pq-p)/q} \diff{}{x}\big\{x^{p/q}\big\}

and, rearranging things,
\diff{}{x}\big\{x^{p/q}\big\}
   & =\frac{p}{q} x^{p-1-(pq-p)/q}

   & =\frac{p}{q} x^{(pq-q-pq+p)/q}

   & =\frac{p}{q} x^{\frac{p}{q}-1}


So finally

  \diff{}{x} \left\{ x^{p/q} \right\} = \frac{p}{q} x^{\frac{p}{q} -1 }

Notice that this has the same form as Lemma , above,  except with n=\frac{p}{q} allowed to be any positive rational  number, not just a positive integer.

By the special case of the quotient rule (Corollary) with g(x)=x^m  and g'(x)=mx^{m-1}


\diff{}{x}\big\{x^{-m}\big\}
=\diff{}{x}\bigg\{\frac{1}{x^m}\bigg\}
=-\,\frac{mx^{m-1}}{{(x^m)}^2}
=-m x^{-m-1}


Again, notice that this has the same form as Lemma,  above, except with n=-m being a negative integer.

In this example we'll use the quotient rule to find the derivative of  x^{-p/q}, for any pair of natural numbers p and q. By the special case the quotient rule (Corollary) with  g(x)=x^{\frac{p}{q}} and g'(x)=\frac{p}{q}x^{\frac{p}{q}-1},


\diff{}{x}\big\{x^{-\frac{p}{q}}\big\}
=\diff{}{x}\bigg\{\frac{1}{x^{\frac{p}{q}}}\bigg\}
=-\,\frac{\frac{p}{q}x^{\frac{p}{q}-1}}{{(x^{\frac{p}{q}})}^2}
=-\frac{p}{q}\ x^{-\frac{p}{q}-1}

subsection.p:
Back in Example we computed the derivative of \sqrt{x} from the  definition of the derivative. The above corollary (correctly) gives


  \diff{}{x} x^{\frac{1}{2}} &= \frac{1}{2} x^{-\frac{1}{2}}


but with far less work.

ul.li:
	Now, to get the derivative f(x) we use the nfold product rule which was  developed in Example, together with the special case of the quotient rule (Corollary).


	f'(x)&=f'_1f_2f_3\frac{1}{f_4}\frac{1}{f_5}
	+f_1f'_2f_3\frac{1}{f_4}\frac{1}{f_5}
	+f_1f_2f'_3\frac{1}{f_4}\frac{1}{f_5}
	-f_1f_2f_3\frac{f'_4}{f^2_4}\frac{1}{f_5}

	\amp\hskip2.5in-f_1f_2f_3\frac{1}{f_4}\frac{f'_5}{f^2_5}

	&=\Big[\frac{f'_1}{f_1}+\frac{f'_2}{f_2}+\frac{f'_3}{f_3}-\frac{f'_4}{f_4}
	-\frac{f'_5}{f_5}\Big]f_1f_2f_3\frac{1}{f_4}\frac{1}{f_5}

	&=\bigg[\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}(\sqrt{x}-1)}
		   -\frac{1}{2-x}-\frac{2x}{1-x^2}-\frac{1}{2x}
	-\frac{2}{3+2x}\bigg]

        \amp\hskip2.5in\frac{(\sqrt{x}-1)(2-x)(1-x^2)}{\sqrt{x}(3+2x)}


	The trick that we used in going from the first line to the second line, namely multiplying term number j by \frac{f_j(x)}{f_j(x)} is often useful in simplifying the derivative of a product of many  factors

		Also take a look at logarithmic differentiation in  Section.
